Electronic Warfare through Command Modern Operations

Electronic Attack effects on Radar Detection (I)

This document aims to provide an introduction to the users of Command Modern Operations regarding the use of electronic warfare and understanding its functionality through various simplified tests. The primary goal is to enable users to grasp the basics of each parameter involved in electronic warfare and gain a fundamental understanding of its operations. By exploring the concepts and conducting straightforward tests, users can enhance their knowledge and proficiency in utilizing electronic warfare capabilities within Command Modern Operations.

Disclaimer: It is important to note that this is a statistical analysis specific to this test scenario and should not be regarded as an absolute truth. Command Modern Operations (CMO) is a simulator based entirely on open-source data and has certain abstractions to ensure playability. CMO is under continuous development in order to offer a simulation as close as possible but with the limitations of any simulator. It is also worth mentioning that real-world situations are often much more complex and cannot be fully captured by these simplified scenarios

What is Electronic Warfare?

As David Adamy cites in his book EW 101: Electronic warfare is defined as the art and science of preserving the use of the electromagnetic spectrum for friendly use while denying its use to the enemy.

Electronic Warfare has historically been categorized into three main groups: Electronic Countermeasures (ECM), Electronic Support Measures (ESM), and Electronic Counter-Countermeasures (ECCM). However, NATO has recently revised the classification and based in the old classification stablish three new groups: Electronic Attack (EA), Electronic Protection (EP), and Electronic Support (ES). Here we will focus on the EA group, focusing specifically on jamming.

Jamming is a technique used to disrupt an enemy's ability to receive important information. It involves sending a strong interfering signal alongside the desired signal to overpower it. The effectiveness of jamming relies on the interfering signal being powerful enough to prevent the enemy from extracting the necessary information from the desired signal. This can occur when the jamming signal overwhelms the desired signal or when the combined signals have characteristics that make it difficult for a processor to extract the desired information.

For more info: EW 101: An introduction to Electronic Warfare

The testing process

The extensive simulation capabilities of Command Modern Operations have been utilized for conducting these tests. The integration of the LUA language enables the automation of scenario creation and data collection processes. These tests were performed using the commercial version 1328.5 of the software. The test scenario comprises the following elements:

  • A radar positioned at an elevated point of 6814m, ensuring no line-of-sight interference.
  • An F-16A Falcon aircraft located at 1.5 times the maximum detection distance of the radar, positioned at 270 degrees relative to the radar and at an altitude of 10000m.
  • The presence of an electronic warfare aircraft, with its systems activated, aimed at disrupting the radar, depending on the specific scenario.


During the tests, the distance at which the test radar detected the F-16A aircraft was measured. This distance can be presented in two ways: normalized to the maximum detection range of the radar for comparing different radars, or in nautical miles as the actual distance.

EA vs Radars at fixed Range

The first test had 16962 data entries, 348 radars, 1 aircraft for detection purpose, 7 EA aircraft and without EA aircraft. This test was carried out with a distance from the jammer to the radar of approximately 75 nmi. The purpose of this test is to assess the capabilities of different platforms when faced with various radar systems at a constant distance, and to observe the degradation of radar detection.

Performance by radar bands

Radar bands refer to specific ranges of frequencies that are used in radar systems to detect and track objects. Each radar band has its own characteristics and advantages depending on the intended application. You can obtain more information about the radar bands in this link

The following graphs display the 7 EA aircraft along with the result without EA. The difference in detection can be observed in both normalized and absolute values. Two aircraft stand out from the rest: the EA-18G and the J-16D.

Performance by EA platform

Now, let's examine each Electronic Attack platform individually. We will analyze their performance against the tested radars using plotted graphs. To assess this performance, we have calculated the percentage reduction in detection for each radar. This is determined by subtracting the normalized detection value without the jammer from the detection value with the jammer present. Multiplying this difference by 100 gives us the percentage reduction in detection caused by the jammer. Next we will see the dispersion of the data. This is important because it is possible that in some radars, for different reasons, the dispersion of the data may be larger.

Detection distance: No EA vs EA EA-18G Growler

The following plot illustrates the correlation between the Detection Distance with and without EA.

Radars that were part of two bands and did not represent a significant sample have been grouped and included within the first band they operated in, for the purpose of simplification.

% reduction in radar capabilities

The following plot illustrates the no normalize detection range of all radars without electronic warfare (EW) on the X-axis. The Y-axis represents the percentage reduction in detection range, where 100% indicates no detection in the presence of EA-18G Growler (EA) carried out by the radar.

Radars that were part of two bands and did not represent a significant sample have been grouped and included within the first band they operated in, for the purpose of simplification.

The following chart provides a comparison of the platform with the rest of the Electronic Attack (EA) platforms as a whole. The scoring of the platform is calculated as 1 minus the mean of the normalized detection values. The scoring of the rest of the platforms is determined in the same way, excluding this particular platform from the mean calculation.

Comparison between platforms

The comparison presented here is calculated as \(100 \cdot \left(1 - \frac{{DR_{EA}}}{{DR_{NoEA}}}\right)\).

Where DR_EA is the mean of all normalize detection distances with EA and DR_NoEA is the mean of all normalize detection distance without EA presence.

Histogram

In this chart, we can observe the distribution of the percentage reduction in detection capability. This provides us with an insight into the quality of the various platforms.
